%N A389713 a(1) = 3, a(2) = 5, a(n) is the smallest prime such that a(n) - a(n-1) + 1 is in the sequence.
%C A389713 It is unknown whether this sequence is infinite.
%D A389713 Paul Erdős and Ronald Graham, Old and new problems and results in combinatorial number theory, Monographies de L'Enseignement Mathématique (1980).
%H A389713 Michael S. Branicky, <a href="/A389713/b389713.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%H A389713 Thomas Bloom, <a href="https://www.erdosproblems.com/472">Problem #472</a>, Erdős Problems.
%e A389713 a(3) = a(1) + a(2) - 1 = 7.
%e A389713 The first prime missing from this sequence is 97, because 97 - 89 + 1 = 9, which is not prime.
%t A389713 a={3,5}; For[i=3,i<100,i++,AppendTo[a,Module[{p=NextPrime@a[[-1]]},While[Not@MemberQ[a,p-a[[-1]]+1],p=NextPrime[p]];p]]]; a
%o A389713 (Python)
%o A389713 from gmpy2 import next_prime
%o A389713 from itertools import islice
%o A389713 def agen():
%o A389713     aset, an = {3}, 5
%o A389713     yield 3
%o A389713     while True:
%o A389713         yield an
%o A389713         aset.add(an)
%o A389713         p, ub = next_prime(an), 2*an - 1
%o A389713         while p - an + 1 not in aset and p <= ub:
%o A389713             p = next_prime(p)
%o A389713         if p > ub:
%o A389713             print("Sequence is finite")
%o A389713             return
%o A389713         an = int(p)
%o A389713 print(list(islice(agen(), 58))) # _Michael S. Branicky_, Jan 09 2026
